India debates Iraq troops request<br>
From Satinder Bindra, CNN New Delhi Bureau Chief<br>
Tuesday, June 17, 2003 Posted: 1451 GMT (10:51 PM HKT)<br>
<br>
<br>
  <br>
The troop request has received a mixed response among politicians. <br>
<br>
 <br>
NEW DELHI (CNN) -- The Indian government is considering a request from the United States to send more than 15,000 troops to Iraq to serve as a stabilization force, senior Indian officials have told CNN. <br>
<br>
A Pentagon team, led by Assistant Secretary of Defense Peter Rodman, visited New Delhi Monday to clarify issues about troop deployment. <br>
<br>
The request has received a mixed reception among politicians. <br>
<br>
&quot;They're asking us now to become sitting ducks for Iraqi snipers in a war that was not of our making and in a war which does not serve any particular Indian interest,&quot; said Mani Shankar Aiyar, an Indian opposition politician. <br>
<br>
Many in India opposed the U.S.-led war in Iraq. There were several protests and the country's parliament even passed a resolution criticizing U.S. actions. <br>
<br>
But senior members of the Indian government are favorably inclined toward the U.S. proposal, and several analysts believe New Delhi could use its participation as a way of winning President Bush's assistance leaning on Pakistan to rein in groups that launch terror attacks against India. <br>
<br>
The government is trying to build a consensus among its coalition partners over the proposal. <br>
<br>
To alleviate Indian concerns that their troops would be taking orders from U.S. generals, senior American officials have agreed to let them operate under an Indian flag, and the Indians would not be expected to take part in combat missions, the Indian officials said. <br>
<br>
&quot;Sending Indian troops to Iraq would symbolize not only the growing U.S.-Indian friendship,&quot; said Brahma Chellaney, a political analyst, &quot;more importantly, it will convey to the Bush administration and to the larger American political system that India is an ally of the United States.&quot; <br>
<br>
Sheikh Rashid Ahmed, Pakistan's information minister, said Pakistan is &quot;concerned&quot; about the possibility of the Indian troop deployment. &quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
Yeah, THATs a good idea! Lets ask a country that has been having some of the worst religious conflicts in the region to come patrol Iraq. Nah, won't seem like the US  has some sort of agenda against Muslims AT ALL!<br>
<br>
Oh , did anyone hear something about the US considering requesting UN or US troops to be sent to Palestine/Israel?  <br>
<br>
